“It is not a hopeless situation, even after three years of problems,” said Terry Gangadin, Director for Guyana Boundless, a Non-Profit Organization dedicated to providing support services and workshops to help Marriage and Family. “It is never too late. There is always hope.”

Gangadin said relationships must come first, before money, before money, before children, before positions. Faith in God is a must along with patience, kindness, commitment and proficiency to resolve conflicts as a resolution, she said.

Her Organization provides stress management, holistic health and wellness, marriage and communication, marital enrichment and orientation for single mothers.

“For us to deal with this issue, we need to go to very young adult and enhance the marriage life because they are the foundation of families,” she said. “If they don’t have a good relationship at home, they can’t have it outside. That is why teen marriage is good because it is not based upon sex but primarily love.

“We advocate teen matrimony but when they are ready the information is there.”

Haverfield Pierre, national representative for Fellowship of Christian and Reformed Churches, said men need to trust the Lord, his wife and he said He must lead better in the family.
